\pard \ {\fs28    }{\b\fs28 1. A. githago}{\fs28  L., }{\i\fs28 Sp. Pl.}{\fs28  435 (1753) (}{\i\fs28 Lychnis githago}{\fs28  (L.) Scop.; incl. }{\i\fs28 A. linicola }{\fs28 Terechov). Plant covered with long, appressed, greyish hairs; stems 30-100 cm. Leaves usually linear, slightly connate, acute, or the lower obtuse. Calyx 3-7 cm, the ovoid or oblong tube usually much shorter than the often caducous teeth. Petals shorter than calyx; limb not spotted, dull purple, rarely white. Seeds mostly 3 mm or more, with prominent, acute tubercles. 2n = 48.}{\i\fs28  Probably native in Europe only in the E. Mediterranean region; introduced as a weed of cultivation almost throughout Europe, but much less abundant than formerly, and extinct in some parts.}{\fs28  All except Sb, but in Az Fa Is only as a rare casual.
\par 
\par Plants from flax-fields in Russia (var. }{\i\fs28 linicola}{\fs28  (Terechov) Hammer) have a narrower, less hairy calyx-tube and smaller and less tuberculate seeds.
\par 
\par    }{\b\fs28 2. A. gracile}{\fs28  Boiss., }{\i\fs28 Diagn. Pl. Or. Nov.}{\b\fs28  3}{\fs28 (}{\b\fs28 1}{\fs28 ): 80 (1854). Like }{\b\fs28 1}{\fs28  but smaller, more slender and less hairy; calyx-tube narrower, equalling or longer than teeth; petals longer than calyx; limb pale purple, with lines of black spots at base.}{\i\fs28  E.C. Greece}{\fs28  (}{\i\fs28 near Farsala}{\fs28 ). Gr. (}{\i\fs28 Anatolia.}{\fs28 )
